Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Neville was born in 1235, in Pickhill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Jollan de Neville, was 48 and her mother, Maud Beauchamp, was 41. She had at least 1 son with William Warde. She died in 1300, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1235–1300":"1235–1300","1228–1295":"1228–1295","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","1230–1266":"1230–1266","1287–1300":"1287–1300","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1195–1238":"1195–1238","1228":"1228","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1246":"1246","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1233":"1233","1287":"1287","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1195":"1195","Pickhill, Yorkshire, England":"Pickhill, Yorkshire, England","Assington, Suffolk, England":"Assington, Suffolk, England","Pickhill, Yorkshire, , England":"Pickhill, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Guiseley, Yorkshire, , England":"Guiseley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1235–1300":"1235–1300","1228–1295":"1228–1295","1233–Female":"1233–Kuollut","1230–1266":"1230–1266","1287–1300":"1287–1300","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1195–1238":"1195–1238","1228":"1228","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1246":"1246","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1233":"1233","1287":"1287","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1195":"1195","Pickhill, Yorkshire, England":"Pickhill, Yorkshire, England","Assington, Suffolk, England":"Assington, Suffolk, England","Pickhill, Yorkshire, , England":"Pickhill, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Guiseley, Y